What if you have any reasonably sized application and uses environment variables to reference special bits of data such as API Keys, tokens or other secretsâ“How will you manage them in K8â“

Thankfully ğŸ™ , Kubernetes solves this problem with Secrets (for confidential ğŸ”’ data) and ConfigMaps (for non-confidential data).

#ConfigMaps ğŸ—º 

A ConfigMap is an API object used to store non-confidential data in key-value pairs. It is used to pass configuration data in form of key-value pairs in K8s.
When a key-value pair is created in ConfigMap then you can inject ğŸ’‰ that ConfigMap into the pod and that can be reusedğŸ”into multiple pods.

â© kubectl create configmap <configmap_name> --from-literal=key1=value1 --from-literal=key2=value2

#SecretsğŸ”’

A Secret is an object that contains a small amount of sensitive ğŸ“’  data such as a password, a token, or a key ğŸ— . Secrets are base64 encoded. There are several types of Secrets to choose from such as tls, opaque, etc.....
Opaque is the default Secret type. When you create a Secret using kubectl, you must use the "generic" subcommand to indicate an Opaque Secret type.

â©kubectl create secret generic <secret_name> --from-literal=key1=value1 --from-literal=key2=value2

Note ğŸ—’ğŸ—’ğŸ—’
ğŸ”¸ Both ConfigMaps and Secrets can be used at the pod level or as volumes mounted in specific paths within a pod.
ğŸ”¸Secrets are not encrypted, only encoded. So one of the best practice using secrets to make it safer is by "Enabling Encryption at Rest" so they are stored encrypted ğŸ”‘ in ETCD. 
